    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2427569430" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2427569430" />
    <a title="Nikhil" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11619849-nikhil"><img alt="Nikhil" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1344276050p2/11619849.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2427569430?book_show_action=true">Jul 16, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nikhil" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nikhil" href="/user/show/11619849-nikhil">Nikhil</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143107361" href="/book/show/18693722-devil-on-the-cross">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11619849-nikhil?shelf=poco">poco</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11619849-nikhil?shelf=african">african</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2427569430" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14187673570945878369">2.5/5. In many ways this text doesn’t work. The speeches at the devil s feast are both too long, and implausibly incorrect (you cannot commodify air because it is non-excludable; you can ration access to healthier neighborhoods on the basis of money via private housing markets). These speeches interrupt the narrative flow and are tedious to read. Other parts of the text are quite funny, however, like the first road trip the people take to ilmorog. <br/><br/>Regarding Ngugi’s critique of capitalism: the fu</span>
  <span id="freeText14187673570945878369" style="display:none">2.5/5. In many ways this text doesn’t work. The speeches at the devil s feast are both too long, and implausibly incorrect (you cannot commodify air because it is non-excludable; you can ration access to healthier neighborhoods on the basis of money via private housing markets). These speeches interrupt the narrative flow and are tedious to read. Other parts of the text are quite funny, however, like the first road trip the people take to ilmorog. <br /><br />Regarding Ngugi’s critique of capitalism: the fundamental feature of a capitalist economic system is decentralized markets. Even with communal ownership of some resources and certain types of state interventions for redistribution and to correct market failures, you would still maintain decentralized markets as a method of organizing the economy because a planned economy is doomed to failure due to incentive problems and information problems. Ngugi seems to attack many of the political economy feature of Kenya’s crony capitalism state (ie the subversion of the state to owners of commodity extraction processes). Ironically, economists and capitalists would share his critique of these features. Ngugi goes wrong in his adherence to certain Marxist ideas like the labor theory of value. A production function needs both labor and capital. Labor is often remunerated poorly due to violence (cooptation of the state), market power by employers, and infinite labor supply problems. <br /><br />Regarding Ngugi’s post colonialism: the text has an interesting subversion of Western tropes of literature that ultimately amount to a form of post colonial critique of modernity. For example, the trope of the woman ruined by modernity throwing herself in front of a train (ie Anna Karenina) is the start of the characters journey and not the end. Similarly the musician poet obsessed with the great National Romantic tone poem is impotent and left stranded, unable to choose in which direction to go. I do think Ngugi remains somewhat beholden to the idea of the nation state and the nation as a meaningful term for a group of people. Of course, the nation state is as insidious if not more insidious a Western import as crony capitalism. It is unclear to me why Ngugi persists in the rhetorical device of striving towards a better conventionally defined nation state rather than exploding the idea of the nation (ie control of borders and labeling of the other) entirely. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14187673570945878369" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


