<div id="review_3078469793" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3078469793" />
    <a title="Brandon Ngacho" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/97586531-brandon-ngacho"><img alt="Brandon Ngacho" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1558580206p2/97586531.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3078469793?book_show_action=true">Dec 19, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brandon Ngacho" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brandon Ngacho" href="/user/show/97586531-brandon-ngacho">Brandon Ngacho</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3078469793" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3745528357621355908">Dear Ngugi wa Thiong&apos;o,<br/><br/>I am ashamed of myself, and my country too. That we couldnt find much use for your brilliance here at home; that only the west could use all this wisdom you had all stuffed up.<br/><br/>I must confess that I regret not reading many of your works. Even worse, I am sorry I don&apos;t understand Gikuyu, and cannot therefore read your original works-I believe something is always lost during translation. <br/><br/>Your book is brilliant in many ways, it tells of everyday stories. You describe Nairobi a</span>
  <span id="freeText3745528357621355908" style="display:none">Dear Ngugi wa Thiong'o,<br /><br />I am ashamed of myself, and my country too. That we couldnt find much use for your brilliance here at home; that only the west could use all this wisdom you had all stuffed up.<br /><br />I must confess that I regret not reading many of your works. Even worse, I am sorry I don't understand Gikuyu, and cannot therefore read your original works-I believe something is always lost during translation. <br /><br />Your book is brilliant in many ways, it tells of everyday stories. You describe Nairobi as it is, you describe our country's situation as it is. Though we gained independence in 1963, we are still colonized by many things: corruption, greed, and many others. Where will all the help come from?<br /><br />Everyday seems like the Devil's feast, as thieves gather to boast of who knows how to steal better, yet we remain silent. I'll do you (and myself) a favor, I'll convince most-if not all-of my friends to read this book, maybe they will be tempted to take action. But then again, how many have the courage of Muturi and Wangari?<br /><br />I very much enjoyed your book. Your language is simple, and to the point. The plot twists are many, and totally enjoyable too. Thank you for the great work. <br /><br />Yours Sincerely,<br />A mere reader.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3745528357621355908" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


